english:
  title: Idle Jottings
  author: Im Yujung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Ten thousand miles of rivers and lakes—a dream,
    Clear waters flowing.
    Thousand mountains thick with tangerines and pomelos—
    Awarded halls.
    On cool stone steps, crickets sing their song,
    Wisdom rounds and turns.
    On warm sand, mandarin ducks drift in slumber—
    Dufu's ancient verse.
    Deeds depart, yet blue mountains remain,
    Qian Gongfu's wisdom.
    With office duties light, the daylight stretches long,
    Wang Yuchen's thought.
    How many days does human life hold?
    Counted on fingers, mere handful.
    Lu Tong reminds us true.
    Drink deeply, deeply of the wine—
    Whether fortune comes or stays away,
    Dufu's way.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This poem is composed of literary allusions and quoted lines from celebrated Chinese poets, each attribution noted in the original. The work creates a meditation on transience and contentment through these borrowed voices.
  - key: ''
    value: The named locations (Clear Waters, Awarded Halls) appear to reference actual places or literary references known to the educated Korean reader of the period.
  - key: ''
    value: Dufu's name appears twice, suggesting the poet's particular affinity for this Tang master's philosophical perspective on life and acceptance.
